Please note that this only works for Spring MVC out of the box. If you wish to use the `XmlMapper`, the counterpart of the `ObjectMapper`, in Spring Security, you have to inject a bean. Problem is, that Spring doesn&#39;t register a bean of type `XmlMapper` by default.

If you just want to use XML serialization you can do the following:

    @Bean
    @Primary
    public XmlMapper xmlMapper(MappingJackson2XmlHttpMessageConverter converter) {
        return (XmlMapper) converter.getObjectMapper();
    }

After this you can inject a bean of type `XmlMapper` in your filter.

